r energizing me at the start of a writing session. And seriously, Delirium could have had this as a sub-title! &quot;The Cure&quot; by Tegan and Sara I love listening to Tegan and Sara and their moodyÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½but somehow optimisticÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½songs. The title couldnÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢t be more a propos, obviously. &quot;I Am A Rock&quot; by Simon &amp; Garfunkel This song is all about trying to be strong and self-sufficientÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½to deny the interdependence of people. I definitely think the characters in Delirium are trying to be rocks, and often not succeeding. &quot;Better&quot; by Regina Spektor She asks over and over, Will you feel anything at all? Enough said. &quot;Say No To Love&quot; by The Pains Of Being Pure At Heart I listened to it the first time just because of the title . . . and lo and behold! ItÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s also just a great song. On a side note: The cover art is fabulous and also Delirium-esque. &quot;Steer&quot; by Missy Higgins This is one of those anthems that pushes you forwardÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½a good post break-up song but also a good song for remembering youÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢re in control of your own destiny. &quot;Somewhere Only We Know&quot; by Keane I picture this song playing during some of the quieter, more intimate scenes in Delirium. It kind of brings to mind the idea of a secret space, be it physical or just internal. &quot;Free Me&quot; by Joss Stone Full disclosure: This song is often on repeat on my iPod. Great song for fighting back, pushing through, and being an individual. &quot;Most Precarious&quot; by Blues Traveler Blues Traveler is so underratedÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½itÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s ridiculous. And this is my favorite of their unknown songs. The time is now and you donÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢t have longÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ So true, man. So true! &quot;Grey&quot; by Ani DiFranco Even Ani knows the power of the color grey! &quot;The Truth&quot; by James Harrison James is a young musician I know from NYC. When I hear this song, I imagine him as Alex, playing a song to LenaÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½maybe while they're in the Wilds! His sound is so stripped-down and also so honest. &quot;They CanÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢t Take That Away From Me&quot; by George Gershwin, as sung by Frank Sinatra Nothing like some old school romanceÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½they knew how to do it back in the day. This reminds me of a song LenaÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s mom would have liked. &quot;Who Am I Living For?&quot; by Katy Perry ThereÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s something scary about this song. ItÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s so foreboding and passionateÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½and I love it. &quot;Poses&quot; by Rufus Wainwright I think I might be in love with Mr. W. His voice is downright haunting and this is a perfect walking-around-NYC-with-my-headphones-on-and-thinking-about-the-meaning-of-life song. Trust me.
